26 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That:
27 (a) There is a Maryland Licensing Workgroup.
28 (b) The Workgroup consists of the following members:
29 (1) the Commissioner of Financial Regulation, or the Commissioner’s
30 designee;

4 HOUSE BILL 1516
1 (2) the following members jointly appointed by the President of the Senate
2 and the Speaker of the House:
3 (i) one representative of a consumer advocacy organization with
4 general knowledge about financial services, lending services, capital markets, and
5 structured finance;
6 (ii) one representative of a banking institution operating in the
7 State;
8 (iii) one representative of a credit union operating in the State;
9 (iv) one representative of a nonbank mortgage business operating in
10 the State; and
11 (v) one member with expertise in:
12 1. State laws and regulations that impact the chartering,
13 licensing, and supervision of the lending industry within the State; and
14 2. financial products and practices that impact consumers;
15 and
16 (3) the following members appointed by the Governor:
17 (i) one member who has general knowledge about financial services,
18 lending services, capital markets, and structured finance; and
19 (ii) one member of the public.
20 (c) The Commissioner of Financial Regulation, or the Commissioner’s designee,
21 shall serve as the chair of the Workgroup.
22 (d) The Office of Financial Regulation shall provide staff for the Workgroup.
23 (e) A member of the Workgroup:
24 (1) may not receive compensation as a member of the Workgroup; but
25 (2) is entitled to reimbursement for expenses under the Standard State
26 Travel Regulations, as provided in the State budget.
27 (f) The Workgroup shall:
28 (1) subject to subsection (g) of this section, study:

HOUSE BILL 1516 5
1 (i) all licensing statutes and regulations adopted under those
2 statutes concerning the provision of financial services in the State;
3 (ii) the need for and the efficacy of the existing licensing and
4 registration system for actively licensed persons who provide financial services in the State;
5 and
6 (iii) whether there is any benefit to expanding existing licensing or
7 registration systems to persons not already subject to those licensing requirements; and
8 (2) make recommendations regarding:
9 (i) the licensing and registration system for actively licensed
10 persons who provide financial services in the State; and
11 (ii) the expansion of the existing licensing or registration systems to
12 persons not already subject to those licensing requirements.
13 (g) In conducting the study required under subsection (f) of this section, the
14 Workgroup shall, at a minimum, consider the potential impacts, costs, and benefits of its
15 recommendations on:
16 (1) residents of the State;
17 (2) persons facilitating, brokering, making, servicing, or acquiring loans in
18 the State;
19 (3) the availability of credit in the State;
20 (4) the cost of credit in the State compared to other states; and
21 (5) the capital markets, including the volume of secondary market
22 transactions.
23 (h) On or before December 31, 2025, the Workgroup shall report its findings and
24 recommendations to the Governor and, in accordance with § 2–1257 of the State
25 Government Article, the General Assembly.
26 SECTION 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act is an emergency
27 measure, is necessary for the immediate preservation of the public health or safety, has
28 been passed by a yea and nay vote supported by three–fifths of all the members elected to
29 each of the two Houses of the General Assembly, and shall take effect from the date it is
30 enacted. Section 2 of this Act shall remain effective through June 30, 2026, and, at the end
31 of June 30, 2026, Section 2 of this Act, with no further action required by the General
32 Assembly, shall be abrogated and of no further force and effect.

